	<scopecontent>
	<p>JOHN T. HARRIS LETTERS, 1845-1899. A major portion of this subseries consists of letters from Harris's constituents requesting personal favors. The letters from 1860 to 1861 primarily address the issue of Virginia seceding from the Union. Echoing the sentiments of many residents of western Virginia, most of the letters express pro-Unionist feelings and encourage Harris to work for a compromise in the Congress to avert violent conflict. Moreover, the contents of these letters, despite the lack of any letters from him, suggest that Harris worked with and was a close friend of Stephen A. Douglas.
	</p>
	</scopecontent>
